Plain — Semantics
Nerijus Ramanauskas <nerijus@signaintermedia.com>


EVALUATION MODEL

    Plain evaluates a list of statements left to right. Each statement
    is a node: a keyword followed by zero or more arguments. The walker
    evaluates nested sub-expressions [...] and leaves everything else —
    keyword arguments and deferred blocks { } — for the called procedure
    to handle. This means each procedure decides which arguments to
    resolve to values and which to treat as raw names.

    Blocks ({ }) are intentionally deferred — the walker leaves them
    unevaluated so procedures like if and repeat can decide if/when/how
    many times to run them.


STATEMENT vs EXPRESSION

    A statement is a top-level node (no parent). Its return value is
    usually discarded.

    An expression is a node wrapped in [...]. The walker evaluates it
    recursively and substitutes its result as an argument value.

        print [add 1, 2]    ` [add 1, 2] is an expression here


VARIABLES AND FRAMES

    Variables are name-to-value bindings stored in a frame. Frames are
    linked in a chain (lexical scoping): a lookup walks from the innermost
    frame outward until the name is found.

    Assignment is done with set:

        set x, 42
        set name, "Plain"

    set keeps a keyword argument as a raw name (the variable to assign)
    and resolves the second argument to its value. This lets set, define,
    and object choose what to do with their keyword arguments without any
    special treatment in the evaluator.


CALLABLES

    A callable is a stored routine that can be invoked by name, stored in
    a variable, and passed as an argument. There is a single kind: define.

    Named definition form:

        define name {parameters} {body}

    The name can be a keyword, a quoted string, or an operator symbol:

        define square {n} { return [* n, n] }
        define 'greet' {name} { print "Hi, {name}" }

    Anonymous (expression) form — returns a callable value:

        set double, [define {n} { return [* n, 2] }]

    Because define creates a regular mutable binding, any name can be
    redefined later using set:

        define greet {name} { print "Hello, {name}!" };
        set greet, [define {name} { print "Hey, {name}." }]

    Callables capture the frame in which they were defined (see CLOSURES).


STRING INTERPOLATION

    Quoted strings containing unescaped braces are automatically
    expanded at parse time. The tokenizer synthesizes a join expression
    from the literal parts and interpolated values:

        "Score: {score}"         ` equivalent to [join "Score: " score]
        "{a} + {b} = {+ a, b}"   ` equivalent to [join a " + " b " = " [+ a, b]]

    {name} inserts the value of a variable. {[expression]} inserts
    the result of an arbitrary expression. Both forms convert values
    to strings automatically (same coercion rules as join).

    Strings without braces are treated as plain strings with no extra
    cost. Use \{ and \} to produce literal brace characters:

        "use \{name\} for interpolation"    ` literal braces, no expansion


BUILT-IN PROCEDURES

    Built-in procedures (if, repeat, set, define, add, etc.) are
    registered as mutable callables in the root frame at startup.
    Because they are regular bindings they can be overridden, stored,
    passed as arguments, and invoked exactly like user-defined callables:

        set op, add;
        print [op 3, 4]    ` 7

        set add, [define {a; b} { return [+ a, b, 1] }]

    set — assignment

        set name, value

    Binds or rebinds the name in the nearest enclosing frame. The first
    argument stays as a raw keyword (the name); the second is resolved.

    if — condition chains

        if condition {then}
        if condition {then} else {else}
        if condition {then} else condition {then} else condition {then} else {else}

    "else" followed by a block is the final fallback. "else" followed by
    any non-block value is an elseif condition; the chain continues.

    when — value dispatch

        when target
            value1 {body1}
            value2 {body2}
            else   {default}

    Compares the target against each value using equality. Executes the
    body of the first match and stops. "else" provides a fallback when no
    case matches. Works with strings, integers, reals, and booleans.

    repeat — loop forms

        repeat {body}                              infinite loop (use break to exit)
        repeat count {body}                        counted loop (runs count times)
        repeat {condition} {body}                  conditional loop (while condition is true)
        repeat {variable} times count {body}       counted loop with automatic variable binding

    The last form creates a scoped variable that counts from 0 to count-1:

        repeat {i} times 5 { print i }             prints 0, 1, 2, 3, 4

    The variable lives in a child frame and does not leak into the outer
    scope. The modifier keyword "times" is extensible — future modifiers
    can follow the same natural-language pattern.

    arithmetic — variadic prefix callables

        +  -  *  /  %   (also: add, subtract, multiply, divide, modulo)

    Accept two or more arguments and fold left to right:

        [+ 1, 2, 3]        ` 6
        [* 2, 3, 4]        ` 24

    comparison — binary prefix callables

        =  !=  <  >  <=  >=   (also: equal, not_equal, less, greater, less_equal, greater_equal)

    Strictly binary — exactly two arguments.

    logic — variadic prefix callables

        and   or   not

    and and or accept any number of arguments and short-circuit.
    not takes exactly one argument.


OPERATORS AS REGULAR CALLABLES

    All operator symbols (+, -, *, /, %, =, !=, <, >, <=, >=) are
    registered as regular mutable callables, identical to any other
    procedure. They can be overridden, stored, and passed:

        set plus, +;
        print [plus 3, 4]    ` 7

        set +, [define {a; b} { return [multiply a, b] }];
        print [+ 3, 4]       ` 12  (overridden to multiply)


CLOSURES

    Every callable captures the frame in which it was defined.
    When invoked, the callable's own frame is created as a child of
    the captured frame, not the caller's frame. This means outer
    variables stay accessible and mutable — enabling counter
    factories, partial application, and all other closure patterns.

    set (x = value) updates the nearest enclosing frame where the
    name is already bound; a new local is created only if the name
    does not exist anywhere in the chain.


RETURN, BREAK, CONTINUE

    return [value]   exits the current callable and yields a value.
    break            exits the nearest repeat loop.
    continue         skips to the next iteration of the nearest repeat.

    All three propagate as special signals through the evaluator.


TYPE INTROSPECTION

    type value       returns a string describing the value's type:
                     "boolean", "integer", "real", "string", "keyword",
                     "list", "callable", "object", or "nil".

    do {block}       evaluates the block in a fresh child scope and returns
                     its value. Variables created inside do not leak out.
                     `return` inside the block yields the do expression's value.


CLASSES AND OBJECTS

    Classes are built from two plain concepts: define for the constructor
    and object for the instance.

    object {block} evaluates the block in a fresh child frame and returns
    that frame as an object value. Fields and methods are created by set
    and define inside the block. self is automatically bound to the
    instance so methods can pass the object itself as a value.

    The constructor is a regular define that returns [object { ... }]:

        define Dog {name; age}:
            return [object {
                define bark {} { print "{name} says Woof!" };
                define info {} { return "{name}, age: {age}" };
                define rename {new_name} { set name, new_name }
            }]

    Constructing an instance:

        set dog, [Dog "Rex", 3]

    Method call — same syntax as any other statement/expression:

        dog bark                  ` statement
        set result, [dog info]    ` expression

    Field access — any binding in the object frame is reachable:

        print [dog name]          ` works if name was explicitly set inside the block

    Constructor parameters are visible to methods via the closure chain
    (the object frame's parent is the constructor's frame). To expose a
    param as an externally accessible field, set it inside the block:

        define Dog {name; age}:
            return [object {
                set name, name;   ` expose as public field
                set age, age;
                define bark {} { print "{name} says Woof!" }
            }]

    All methods are defined with define and are mutable bindings.

    Implicit self: methods access fields and other methods directly
    through the closure chain without explicit self. self is only needed
    when passing the instance itself as a value:

        define Node {value}:
            return [object {
                define get_self {} { return self }
            }]

    Constructors are regular callables — they can be stored, passed, and
    overridden like anything else:

        set Cat, [define {name} {
            return [object {
                define meow {} { return "{name} meows" }
            }]
        }];
        set cat, [Cat "Whiskers"];
        print [cat meow]    ` Whiskers meows

    Stateful object — counter pattern:

        define Counter {}:
            return [object {
                set count, 0;
                define increment {} { set count, [+ count, 1] };
                define value {} { return count }
            }]

        set counter, [Counter];
        counter increment;
        counter increment;
        print [counter value]    ` 2


HOST EXTENSION

    The host application can supply a handler function on
    PLAIN_CONTEXT that is called for any keyword not found in the frame.
    This is how the Inspector implements print without the library
    containing any I/O.
